# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#  Line-ending policy. Without this, Windows developers + Linux CI/
#  server end up with files that differ only by CRLF vs LF — which
#  is harmless for most source code but catastrophic for two things:
#
#    1. Flyway migration files. Flyway computes a CRC32 over the raw
#       bytes of the .sql file when it applies a migration, and stores
#       that checksum in flyway_schema_history. The next boot validates
#       the current file's checksum against the stored one. Different
#       line endings → different bytes → different checksum →
#       "Migration checksum mismatch for migration version N" →
#       Spring Boot refuses to start → entire service crash-loops →
#       gateway returns 503 for all its endpoints (states list fails,
#       building list fails, etc.). This was the exact symptom we were
#       chasing "frequently" before this rule landed.
#
#    2. Shell scripts. Bash chokes on CRLF in shebang lines + heredocs.
#
#  Default policy: text files auto-detect EOL on commit but check out
#  with LF. This means the working tree on Windows shows LF, the repo
#  stores LF, and the Linux deploy gets LF. No surprises.
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

* text=auto eol=lf

# ─── Lock specific files / extensions to LF unconditionally ───
# Flyway migrations — checksum-sensitive (see header above).
*.sql               text eol=lf
# Shell scripts — bash chokes on CRLF.
*.sh                text eol=lf
# Java / Kotlin — keep LF for cross-platform git-diff sanity.
*.java              text eol=lf
*.kt                text eol=lf
# YAML / properties — Spring Boot tolerates either, but LF keeps diffs clean.
*.yaml              text eol=lf
*.yml               text eol=lf
*.properties        text eol=lf
# Docker + nginx config
Dockerfile          text eol=lf
*.dockerfile        text eol=lf
nginx.conf          text eol=lf
docker-compose*.yml text eol=lf

# ─── Genuine binary files — never touch ───
*.png   binary
*.jpg   binary
*.jpeg  binary
*.gif   binary
*.ico   binary
*.pdf   binary
*.zip   binary
*.jar   binary
*.class binary
